opportunities for startup founders are rapidly closing as major tech companies acquire or launch competing products. Context includes recent major acquisitions: Cursor completed $900M funding with valuation near $10B, Google acquired Windsurf for $2.4B (launched December 2024), and AWS launched Kiro AI programming tool. The article covers market dynamics and competitive landscape for new entrants.\",\n    25→    \"author\": \"OFweek AI\",\n    26→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n    27→    \"url\": \"https://mp.ofweek.com/ai/a556714706507\",\n    28→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-26\",\n    29→    \"topics\": [\"AI coding market\", \"startups\", \"acquisitions\", \"competition\"],\n    30→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n    31→  },\n    32→  {\n    33→    \"title\": \"Fireship: How to Make Vibe Coding Not Suck - 7 Essential MCP Servers\",\n    34→    \"description\": \"Fireship released a video discussing the current state of AI coding, highlighting how some developers are abandoning AI due to reliability issues (like Streamer Coding Garden) while others are significantly boosting productivity (like NVIDIA employees). The video covers 7 essential MCP (Model Context Protocol) servers to avoid the 'prompt hell treadmill' - a vicious cycle where developers waste credits without getting desired results - and improve AI coding reliability.\",\n    35→    \"author\": \"Fireship\",\n    36→    \"source\": \"YouTube\",\n    37→    \"url\": \"https://www.youtube.com/@Fireship\",\n    38→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-25\",\n    39→    \"topics\": [\"Vibe Coding\", \"MCP servers\", \"AI coding tools\", \"productivity\"],\n    40→    \"type\": \"tutorial\"\n    41→  },\n    42→  {\n    43→    \"title\": \"Claude Code Usage Experience - 1.5 Months of Intensive Vibe Coding\",\n    44→    \"description\": \"Detailed analysis of 'Vibe Coding' - deep AI-assisted programming after 1.5 months of intensive Claude Code usage. Explains what tasks LLMs excel at (understanding code logic, creating diagrams, rapid prototyping) and identifies tasks where LLMs struggle (100% accuracy requirements, complex debugging). Provides practical insights on when to use AI coding tools versus traditional approaches.\",\n    45→    \"author\": \"喵神 (Miao Shen)\",\n    46→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n    47→    \"url\": \"https://new.qq.com/rain/a/LNK2025081008329400\",\n    48→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-25\",\n    49→    \"topics\": [\"Claude Code\", \"Vibe Coding\", \"LLM capabilities\", \"practical experience\"],\n    50→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n    51→  },\n    52→  {\n    53→    \"title\": \"Stanford Launches Vibe Coding Tutorial - AI Development Course\",\n    54→    \"description\": \"Stanford released a new course offering on 'Coding LLMs and AI Development' covering LLM training principles, effective prompt engineering, open-source tools like GitNexus for reducing AI Coding failure rates, and discussion of how LLM Agent capabilities (especially Claude and Codex) crossed a coherence threshold in late 2025. The course addresses the growing demand for 'Vibe Coding' skills.\",\n    55→    \"author\": \"Stanford University\",\n    56→    \"source\": \"TechMedia\",\n    57→    \"url\": \"https://news.qq.com/rain/a/20260224A06NX300\",\n    58→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-24\",\n    59→    \"topics\": [\"Vibe Coding\", \"LLM training\", \"prompt engineering\", \"AI education\"],\n    60→    \"type\": \"tutorial\"\n    61→  },\n    62→  {\n    63→    \"title\": \"AI Programming Reached Critical Threshold in December 2025 - Andrej Karpathy\",\n    64→    \"description\": \"Andrej Karpathy declared that AI programming underwent a fundamental qualitative change in December 2025. Before December, he considered coding agents 'basically useless,' but after December 2025, everything changed with significantly improved model quality, stronger long-term consistency, and ability to complete large, time-consuming tasks. He introduced the concept of 'Vibe Coding' - a paradigm where AI has crossed a threshold enabling people to build programs using natural language alone. His own work pattern shifted from '80% hand-coded + 20% Agent-assisted' to '80% Agent-coded + 20% human refinement' by December 2025. In one example, an AI agent completed a complex multi-step task in just 30 minutes that previously took him an entire weekend.\",\n    65→    \"author\": \"Andrej Karpathy\",\n    66→    \"source\": \"Twitter/Blog\",\n    67→    \"url\": \"https://twitter.com/karpathy\",\n    68→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-24\",\n    69→    \"topics\": [\"AI programming\", \"Vibe Coding\", \"LLM agents\", \"paradigm shift\"],\n    70→    \"type\": \"opinion\"\n    71→  },\n    72→  {\n    73→    \"title\": \"Karpathy's Six Key LLM Breakthroughs of 2025\",\n    74→    \"description\": \"In his annual summary, Karpathy highlighted six major breakthroughs that enabled the AI programming transformation: 1) RLVR (Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards), 2) Jagged Intelligence, 3) Cursor's Next-Generation Application Layer, 4) Claude Code Local Agents, 5) Vibe Coding, and 6) Nano Banana LLM GUI. He also purchased an M4 Mac Mini to research 'Claws' - an emerging AI agent orchestration layer that sits above LLM agents to improve task scheduling, context management, tool calling, and persistence.\",\n    75→    \"author\": \"Andrej Karpathy\",\n    76→    \"source\": \"Blog/Twitter\",\n    77→    \"url\": \"https://blog.csdn.net/wangzhao0012/article/details/158349495\",\n    78→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-24\",\n    79→    \"topics\": [\"LLM breakthroughs\", \"AI agents\", \"Vibe Coding\", \"RLVR\", \"Claws\"],\n    80→    \"type\": \"technical\"\n    81→  },\n    82→  {\n    83→    \"title\": \"Lex Fridman Podcast #482: Pavel Durov on Freedom, Censorship, and Technology\",\n    84→    \"description\": \"Lex Fridman released episode #482 featuring an in-depth 4 hour 34 minute interview with Telegram founder Pavel Durov. The conversation covers topics including Telegram's philosophy, freedom of speech, censorship, money, power, and human nature in the context of modern technology and AI.\",\n    85→    \"author\": \"Lex Fridman\",\n    86→    \"source\": \"Podcast\",\n    87→    \"url\": \"https://www.youtube.com/@lexfridman\",\n    88→    \"published_date\": \"2026-02-24\",\n    89→    \"topics\": [\"AI\", \"freedom\", \"censorship\", \"technology\", \"Telegram\"],\n    90→    \"type\": \"discussion\"\n    91→  }\n    92→]\n    93→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"
